<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-perimeter-of-a-sector-of-a-circle-2">
  <title>Perimeter of a sector of a circle 2</title>

  <activity>
    <statement>
      <sidebyside>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\textbf{Materials Needed:}</m> A4 or colored paper (1 per student), Circular paper or printed circles (like “pizza templates”), Protractors, Rulers, Scissors, String or flexible measuring tape, Calculators and Worksheet or recording sheet
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
              <p>
                Imagine you’ve just cut a slice of pizza from a giant round one. You want to wrap a ribbon around the slice—how long would it need to be?
              </p>
            </li> 
          </ul>
        </p>
        <image source="/paper-fan.png">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
         </image>
      </sidebyside>
        <p>  
          <ul>
              
            <li>
              <p>
                1. Create a Fan Design
              </p>

            <p>  
          (a)  Use a compass to draw a circle with radius 10 cm.
          </p>
          <p>
           (b) Use a protractor to choose any central angle between 45° and 180°.
          </p>
          <p>
            (c) Cut out the sector to form a paper fan.
          </p>
          <p>
           (d) Label the angle and radius.
            </p>
            <p>
              2. Decorate It
            </p>
            <p>
              (a) Use colored pencils or markers to decorate the fan.
            </p>
            <p>
              (b) Patterns, lines, colors
            </p>
            <p>
              (c) Use symbols like sun rays, flowers, etc. to make it visually appealing.
            </p>
            <p>
              3. Measure the Arc Length and record it.
            </p>
            <p>
              4.  Calculate the Arc Length using the formula and compare your answer with the actual measurement.
              <md>
                <mrow> \text{Arc length} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times 2 \pi r</mrow>
              </md>
              <p>
                Where <m>\theta</m> is the angle in degrees and <m>r</m> is the radius.
              </p>
            </p>
            <p>
              5. Calculate the Perimeter of the Sector by Adding the arc length and the two radii.
              <md>
                <mrow> \text{Perimeter} = \amp \text{Arc Length } + 2 r</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
               Math Gallery Walk
            </p>
            <p>
              (a) Display your fan designs by pinning up the decorated fans around the classroom.
            </p>
            <p>
              (b) Each one includes:
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Radius
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Central angle (θ)
                  </p>
                 
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Arc length
                  </p>
                </li><li>
                  <p>
                    Perimeter
                  </p>
                </li>


              </ul>
              Let others walk around and compare the math and designs.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>
      </p>
      
    <p>
      <m>\textbf{Study Questions}</m>
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          What happens to the arc length when you increase the angle?
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          How do larger radii affect the total perimeter?
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Which fan would take the most material to make in real life?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    </statement>
  </activity>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Work out the perimeter of the figure below.
      </p>
      <image>
        <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.15]
        
          % Outer and inner radii
          \def\R{14}
          \def\r{7}
        
          % Fill the ring-shaped semicircle
          \fill[cyan!50!] (0,0) arc(180:0:\R) -- (\R,0)
            arc(0:180:\r) -- cycle;
        
          % Outline
          <!-- \draw[thick] (0,0) arc(180:0:\R); -->
          <!-- \draw[thick] (\R,0) arc(0:180:\r); -->
          <!-- \draw[thick] (0,0)  (\R*2,0); -->
        
          % Labels
          \node at (4,2) {\small $14$ cm};
          \node at (21,2.2) {\small $14$ cm};
          \node at (7,-3) {\footnotesize (Use $\pi = \dfrac{22}{7}$)};
        \end{tikzpicture}
         </latex-image> 
        </image>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Inner semicircle arc:
          <md>
            <mrow> = \amp\frac{1}{2} \times 2 \pi\ r </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp \pi\ r </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp\frac{22}{7} \times 14\,\text{cm}</mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp\ 44 \,\text{cm} </mrow>
          </md>
          Outer semicircle arc:
          <md>
            <mrow> = \amp\frac{1}{2} \times 2 \pi\ r </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp \pi\ r </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp\frac{22}{7} \times 28\,\text{cm}</mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp\ 88 \,\text{cm} </mrow>

          </md>
          Straight diameter line :
          <md>
            <mrow> =\amp 14 \,\text{cm} </mrow>
            <mrow>=\amp 88 \,\text{cm} + 14 \,\text{cm} + 44 \,\text{cm}</mrow>
            <mrow>=\amp 146\,\text{cm}</mrow>
          </md>

        </p>
      </statement>
    </solution>
    </example>


</subsection>